Oct 27 2009 	Loved Excalibur!	I stayed here with my boyfriend for three nights (Wed, Thurs &amp; Friday) and this was my first trip to Vegas. Once we were in our hotel room, I was very happy with it. We booked one of the newer widescreen rooms and asked for a view of the strip. We were told those rooms required an extra $10 a night, so that's what we did.Our room was on the left side of tower 2, and had an incredible view of NYNY and MGM Grand and some of the mountains. And while the TV is nice, there aren't many channels to watch (but who's going to be watching TV in Vegas, right?).The beds were really comfortable, with plenty of pillows, but we later discovered one drawback to having a strip-view room: the sound of traffic is so loud you feel as if you're sleeping right on the street! We fixed this by turning the A/C's fan on to drown the noise out, but those really sensitive to noise might want to avoid these rooms.The room was cleaned, bed made, bathroom supplies restocked each day and the towels were nice and fluffy. The hallways during our stay were kept clean and food carts &amp; trays removed promptly. Our third day there, we discovered that the folder your room key comes in is also a map of the hotel if you unfold it even further, but we'd already figured out the layout by then.For the resort fee of $5, you get 2 free drink credits, 2 free passes to carnival games in the Fantasy Faire Midway and 2 free passes to the fitness center.We didn't use the fitness center or pool area, so can't comment on them.We were approached by the timeshare people and were at first fooled into thinking they were hotel employees trying to help us. As I'd read previous reviews, I quickly figured it out. If you just keep walking, they leave you alone. They are dressed in navy blue suits and are located right next to the tower entrances and the bell desk. We tried the breakfast buffet and was happy with it, but I'm sure there's better elsewhere on the strip. As for location on the strip, I was somewhat happy with this hotel. It is a bit of a hike to the really impressive mid-strip hotels, but a major part of the fun I had in Vegas was exploring the strip. Also, the Deuce bus makes it easy and cheap to get around. We aren't gamblers at all, so while I'd say the casino was dark and smoky, it didn't seem to be that much more so than any other casino we walked through. All in all, we were both very happy with our stay here and felt (at least with the Widescreen view room) it was probably worth more than what we'd paid for and I definitely recommend staying here if you want somewhere nice while sticking to a budget. I'd probably choose somewhere else to stay if we ever visit Vegas again, but that's only for the sake of variety.	
Oct 26 2009 	Some good some bad	Third trip to Vegas in about a year and a half. Have stayed at Ballys, Harrahs and Imperial Palace(twice). Decided to go with Excalibur because I waited too long to book and they had a better deal than any of the HET properties at the time. This trip I decided that I wanted to stay on a weekend night. Flew in on Sat around 3:30 and stayed two nights at Excalibur before moving to my comped nights at Imperial Palace. First thing my opinion about Vegas on a Sat night...basically the same as a weekday night only more people! Got to hotel around 4:30pm, no line for check-in. Front desk lady tried to make me upgrade to widescreen room for $20 extra each night, no thanks paying enough already. Told her that I would like my standard room on a higher floor. She told me that she couldn't give me one if I still wanted a smoking room. Told me it had to be 1st or 2nd floor only in the standard room but if I paid for upgrade I could have one of those rooms higher up. Hmmmm, No thank you again, told I would take 2nd floor...she said we only have 1st floor left. Great! No map of hotel given. Really wished they would have given a map to know what all was in the hotel. Nothing in the room either. Room was in Tower 1, first floor. Didn't need elevator so can't comment on it. Room was next to last room on hall. Had to go all the way to other side of Tower 1 for ice machine. (had to ask directions from security, no map remember?!) Security was usually sitting there by elevator, sign says you need to present room key but no one ever asked. Sales people are completely outta control, they harrass you as soon as you walk in the door for all angles and are always by the entrance to rooms so they get you coming and going! Don't be fooled at first they will make you think they are hotel staff trying to help you check in!!Okay, now to my lovely standard room on the first floor. At first I was completely upset but as it turned out being on the first floor was great!! No waiting for elevators!! Room was quiet, no outside noise, as the view was of a giant wall. There was some space in between and a maintance guy walked by the window one day and scared the crap out of us. Had two double beds, comfortable but only 2 pillows on each. Thank goodness we only used one bed. Got in bed the first night and pulled the covers up to find holes and brown stains....ughhh! Quickly got out and switched beds, that one was better. Room service was good but they did stop me in the hall one day at 11:30 and ask if we were leaving the room at all. Ummm yeah give me a minute lady, I'm on vacation! lol Room had small table and two chairs. Typical small no channel vegas tv. Bathroom was rather large, no tub just shower. Room size for standard room was pretty good size. Went to the pool for about an hour one day. Not packed since it was Oct but nice set up. Pool is located in Tower 2. Didn't do too much gambling here, usually keep on walking out to other hotels. Liked having a base to return to after exploring south end of strip more thorougly. You can walk into Luxor and then into Mandalay Bay without going outside. They also have a free tram connecting them. Liked walking to NYNY, MGM and Tropicana. Bought a 3 day Deuce pass online a head of time and used that to head to the other end of strip and downtown. This hotel has an excellant food court. Loved being able to walk to second floor for quick food options. Ate at McDonalds and Chinese place but they had lots of other stuff to choose from. Also ate at Southwest grill on first floor near Tower 2. Would come back to Excalibur if a good deal came along!!	
Oct 26 2009 	Still value for money!!!	Ok, quick bit of background here. We were heading back to Vegas Oct 12-22, myself, wife, 12yr old son and my folks. We had stayed at the Excalibur same time last year, and this was to be our 5th visit to Vegas in the last 7 years. Got a great deal on Smartervegas.com, $647 for widescreen room for 10 nights. After a long day travelling from Scotland, we hit Vegas at about 2130, grabbed our bags and dived into a taxi. $15 and 10 minutes later, we were at the check in desk!! No lines, served straight away. Tried the $20 trick but check in clerk already rushed through our booking before even asking for ID &amp; CC, so he didn't even get the chance to see the sandwich, lol.... Only upgrade available was view room for extra $15 per night, declined his offer as we knew the rooms booked were good enough. We were on 26th floor, with view of Luxor and Mandalay Bay. Ok, to the rooms....Like i said, we had stayed here the previous year, so knew what to expect. My folks however were at the Ex for the first time, having previously stayed at the Hilton and HGV Club. Everyone was impressed with the rooms, large enough, 2 good sized queen beds in each room, with requested adjoining door. The Excalibur, in my opinion is a great hotel if the price is right, and we certainly got a great deal. We didn't use any of the hotel restaurants, as we had other places we wanted to try, although we did hit Krispy Kreme Doughnuts a few times!!! Service at the hotel was very good from all employees, and this was true when my folks shower had backed up and a maintenance man turned up within 5 minutes of reporting to front desk!!Pool area was good as always, and had 3 out of 4 pools open, and cabana hire for $60 was really good. Tables and slots were pretty tight though, but i felt this was the case at all the casinos this year, not just the Excalibur.Overall, had another great stay at good prices and comfortable rooms.Would recommend to anyone who goes with a realistic expectation. Excalibur is not high end Vegas luxury, but neither is the room rate. If you appreciate you will get good solid 3 star accommodation, good amenities and friendly service, you will have a great time here.	
Oct 25 2009 	Adequate for the money	Stayed for 2 nights in a standard room. Arrived around noon and there was a line of about 30 people to check in. The line moved fairly quickly and I got a non-smoking, 2 bed standard room (no widescreen tv) on the 14th floor. I didn't inquire about any upgrade and wasn't offered any. Got up to the room and it was dated, but clean and functional. Didn't spend that much time in the room or casino. Did not try any of the restaurants here either. Tried to check out via tv, but it said it was unavailable. The location is a detractor. I spent most of my time mid-strip so I wouldn't stay here again unless it was a really good deal. Took the deuce bus up and down the strip. Bought the 3-day pass online and used it to get to Orleans, Rio, Palms. There is a shuttle from Paris to Rio, but I had the 3-day pass and was set on using it. Ate at Bellgio and Wynn buffets and they're both still exceptional. I also took advantage of some coupons online and had a sandwich and soup at Bella Panini in Venetian food court and used the Haagen Daz coupon for ice cream. The meatball sandwich was very good. No complaints about the bed or facilities at Excalibur. I was a bit nervous from reading some negative reviews, but I found everything satisfactory.	
Oct 25 2009 	Cheap and cheerful!	Last year we stayed at the Mirage and the Luxor. This year we wanted somewhere cheaper than the Mirage but did not want to pay too much, so we chose this hotel. Having seen it last year we were prepared for the over-the-top castle theme, but this is Vegas right? You need to get into the spirit of it to enjoy it! We decided to upgrade to a renovated widescreen room and were very happy with it. It was clean, comfy and (despite being told we had not paid for a 'view') had a great outlook over the mountains. Yes the casino was smokey (which casino here is not?) and yes the sales people were annoying (they are in the expensive hotels too and you just have to ignore them) but our room was non-smoking and very quiet. There are, of course, pros and cons of staying here. Pros: connected to the Luxor and Mandalay Bay hotels by free tram good selection of restaurants and food stands cocktails/other drinks much cheaper than the more expensive hotels easier to get a seat on the Deuce bus as it is at the southern end of the stripCons: need to walk a fair distance to get to many of the hotels casino can be quite dark and noisy room service seemed to leave trolleys in corridors for days at a timeAll in all, however, I was very pleasantly surprised by my visit, especially after reading some of the negative comments on this website (I guess people are far more likely to post when they have had a bad experience than a good one) and would certainly consider staying here again. I will also be suggesting this hotel to friends looking for a fun, cheap option when staying in Las Vegas.	
