Aug 12 2009 	Older hotel for families and limited budget	My wife and I just returned from a four day visit to Las Vegas where we stayed at the Excalibur Hotel. The Excalibur is located at one end of the strip, very close to the airport however we did not notice any noise from the airport. The hotel is not bright and “glitzy” like other hotels in Vegas. In fact it is decorated in darker tones. The staff was friendly and helpful. Upon our arrival I tipped the front desk clerk twenty dollars and received an upgraded room on the twenty fifth floor and a twelve o’clock check out time. Upon going to our room we found that the door would not open. We reported the situation to a security guard who went back to our room with us. After trying the door several times he discovered that the doorset was faulty and that you had to jerk the handle in order to get it to open. We then discovered that the door would not close unless you slammed it several times. He said that we should probably report the problem to someone. The next morning I did report the problem to one of the housekeepers on our floor and she stated that she had noticed it wasn’t working the day before when she cleaned the room. She did call and report the problem. I also went to the front desk and reported the problem. The door was repaired by the time we returned from breakfast. We also received a follow-up call from housekeeping asking if the door had been repaired and if it was working properly. The room was good sized but older and rather tired looking. The wallpaper by the window was peeling back, the curtain was missing some of the rings and hanging down. The furnishings showed signs of wear, one of the bed spreads had a hole in it and one of the chairs had a mark where someone had tried to repair the hole in it with tape, but the tape had peeled off long ago. A shower cap from a previous guest was left hanging on the bathroom door for two days. I told the housekeeper about it while she was cleaning our room and it was gone when we returned to our room. We were awakened at 5:30 in the morning to the sound of the fire alarm (but this could happen in any hotel). It turned out to be false alarm. The elevators were efficient with very little wait time. There were time share salesmen in the common areas (as they were in several other hotels) but they were polite, offered assistance and really didn’t bother anyone. The buffet at the hotel was very reasonable and the selection varied. This is a typical buffet with all the usual selection of foods along with Mexican, Italian, and Chinese food bars and a carving station. The lines can be rather long but they move quickly. Again the staff was friendly and efficient. We also went to the Tournament of Kings dinner show. It was different and fun, but one of those things were going once is enough. You eat everything with your hands as there are no eating utensils. Eating broccoli with your hands is very different. I would think that families with younger children will really enjoy this show. The show itself is not great acting, but fun. You cheer for your King as he competes in a various contests.All in all the Excalibur is an older hotel that would benefit from having there rooms updated. If we had an upgraded room I wonder what the standard rooms are like. This hotel is probably best for families, and those looking for a limited budget experience.	
