Aug 10 2009 	a nice perfectly located hotel for the family	We stayed at Excalibur Aug 2-7 (sun-Fri), 2009 with three children, girls, ages 7, 9, and 13, and loved it. We booked directly through Excalibur and got an average nightly rate of $40. Upon arriving, we requested adjoining rooms in Tower II and were offered upgrades for $10 more per night, per room. The cost to upgrade was well worth it, mainly for the proximity to the pool, and for the view of the pool and mountains. Actually, the first rooms they put us in on floor 17 overlooked the roof and a/c units. A call to the front desk landed us rooms on the other side of the hall with spectacular views for no additional cost. The rooms were clean and well-appointed. The beds were comfortable, and the a/c worked great for both rooms. There were no problems with construction noise or other guest noise. The employees, for the most part, were great. On the last two days we were there, the winds in Las Vegas were strong and Excalibur closed all three pools!! This was very disappointing and the front desk was lackadaisical about it, saying it was for guest safety and no compensation would be offered. We went over to the Monte Carlo pools and spent the day there. It was windy, but I didn't see that anyone's life was in danger at the Monte Carlo. We had massages at the Excalibur spa and weren't real impressed with the $60 25-minute back massages -- actually, that was the most disappointing thing about the whole trip. The best things about the trip were the great rooms with views and the uncrowded pools. The other resort pools were jampacked. One day we went to check out the Mandalay Bay pools because they are supposed to be the best. At first, the pool guy at the turnstile said &quot;No entry without a hotel key,&quot; but when my husband gave him a $20, he unabashedly said we were &quot;abolutely welcome in.&quot; It was a nice pool, complete with sand, wave pool, and lazy river, but you have to buy tubes for $23 each!!! Luckily, we met some people who loaned us theirs. The Monte Carlo, whom we didn't have to bribe for entry, charged a reasonable $10 per tube! The Krispy Kreme doughnuts tasted stale, but the McDonalds came in quite handy a time or two. The Regale Italian restaurant is overrated; we paid nearly $100 and the service was horrible. We've had much better meals and service at Olive Garden (a medium price range family eatery in Texas). We ate some at the Excalibur buffet and enjoyed it. For two days, we bought the eat-all-day buffet armband at Luxor. These hotels are connected by moving walkways. The adult price is $29, but the really good deal is for the kids -- just $15 to eat all day (ages 4-11). Check-in and check-out was quick. The arcade was a lot of fun for the kids. Just start out early ignoring the men and women in blue blazers who want to know &quot;where you're from&quot; and &quot;how long you're staying,&quot; to avoid getting tied up talking timeshares. The Excalibur was a nice, perfectly located hotel for the family.	
