Aug 8 2009 	Not bad - you get what you pay for	Not the best hotel iv stayed in. We arrived from the airport via a shuttle bus at the rear rotunda drop off point at the hotel. There were no signs and we had no idea where to check in. We finally found the front desk after walking through the casino (not good with suitcases really). The memeber of staff who checked me in was very rude and didn't speak to me at all. We were put in tower 1 and were given a non-renovated room which was not great but we didn't pay much for the room so I suppose it is only fair. We had no window view at all - just a wall right in front of our room so had no idea where abouts we were. The room and decor was dated and really does need renovating. The bed was comfortable the bedding was not nice. The bathroom was very spacious and clean with a huge mirror and shower which was good. The room was large with a bed, table and chairs and a sofa so it was spacious. We didn't order room service but the people opposite our room did and there dirty trays and food were left outside their room for 3 days!! Incredibly unhygienic!!! There was also glasses left outside from room service that weren't collected and some were broken by the morning. The hotel itself is in a great location with a connecting walk way to new york new york and luxor. Compared to other hotels on the strip the excalibur is definately not luxorious but for the price and the location i probably would stay there again but i would pay the extra to get one of the updated widescreen rooms. There is no free wireless internet which is quite poor as most american hotels do offer this now. Beware of the time share sellers!! They tried to con us into free show tickets the minute after we had checked in. Free tickets in exchange for a full day at one of their resorts - i would suggest saying no staright away unless you have plenty of time in vegas and don't mind losing a day for free show tickets. Personally, i dont think the hotel should allow time share people to bother their guests. We didn't eat in the hotel but would recommend the outback steak house above the coca cola shop. Overall, a good place to rest on a budget but if you want vegas luxury, don't go here.	
Aug 8 2009 	Great place for kids	We just returned home from six nights at the Excalibur, and we were extremely satisfied with our experience. If you read my profile and contributions, you will note that I am almost always satisfied with the hotels I choose. That is because I research them thoroughly and select the ones most likely to provide the experience we are looking for. The reviewer who had to move from the Excalibur to Caesar's Palace was obviously in the wrong place the first time! The two hotels are nothing alike, and for my family, that is a good thing. The Excalibur is a great place for kids. The turrets, drawbridge, and moats may be a bit cheesy, but my grandsons loved them. The Tournament of Kings dinner show was a big hit. No, it is not historically accurate, but we weren't there for a history lesson. Our grandsons did learn about jousting and the legend of King Arthur, and the beautiful horses were an attraction themselves. The dinner was good: tomato soup, a small roasted chicken, broccoli, french fries, rolls, apple turnovers, and pitchers of soda. If you book your stay on the hotel's web site, choose the promotion that includes 2 for 1 tickets to the show. Our boys absolutely loved the 4-D rides and the arcade. Look in free tourist magazines for discount coupons. We stayed on a lower floor on the side facing New York New York, and we never once heard the jackhammer or construction noise another reviewer complained about. We did hear screams from the roller coaster at NYNY, but we considered that part of the Vegas atmosphere, as we didn't go there for peace and quiet. Our room was a double queen with the widescreen TV. It was quite large and was serviced regularly while we were out during the day. The sheets were of high quality, and the towels were new. Bathroom amenities were excellent and were replenished each day. I will agree with another reviewer that the sink counter was unusually high and that the toilet paper holder was not within a child's easy reach.. Also, the room did seem a little dark, but after all, you are staying in a castle!. TV channels were limited, but we had almost no time for TV anyhow. The halls, elevators, and public areas were clean enough, maybe not to the standards of Caesar's Palace, but certainly adequate for a place with so many children and so much foot traffic. We appreciated the fact that there was a McDonalds on site, in addition to a Pizza Hut Express, Quiznos, Krispy-Kreme, and Cold Stone Creamery. Our grandsons would have little interest in the food offerings at Caesar's Palace, and I wouldn't like the price. We were tempted to buy the all-you-can-eat -all-day buffet tickets, but we didn't think our young grandsons would eat $25 worth each day, although that might be a bargain for some people. Shopping venues included souvenir shops and Everything's $10 stores. Again, if your taste runs to Armani and Gucci, for heaven's sake, don't book the Excalibur! The location at the south end of the Strip suited us perfectly. We wanted to see Bodies: The Exhibition at the Luxor, in addition to seeing the Luxor itself, which was right next door. We walked the length of the Strip, visiting every hotel along the way, seeing the light show and conservatory at the Bellagio, Cleopatra's barge at Caesar's Palace, and the volcano at the Mirage. Although we bought a monorail ticket for one day, we found it to be not very helpful. Getting to and from the monorail from the Strip was more trouble than just walking along the Strip, and the Strip was much more interesting. We considered the Deuce bus, but every bus we saw was horribly overcrowded. We just walked, which was best for us anyhow. Yes, there were obscene pictures of boobs scattered on the sidewalk and men (and one very pregnant woman) passing out invitations to Dial-a-Girl, but to me, that is no worse than the advertisements for erectile dysfunction prescriptions that now punctuate primetime TV shows.At least you can reject the offers of the touts; the Viagra ads come into your living room when you are only trying to watch the news. Certainly, the mystique of Sin City is disappearing in our more open and permissive society.The Excalibur itself had heavy security at every exterior entrance and at the entrances to the towers where the rooms were located. There was absolutely no semblance of impropriety there, at least not before midnight when we retired. Dick's Last Resort Restaurant wasn't even doing a good job of looking risque. From the outside it just seemed silly and juvenile, not obscene. Along with our stay at the Excalibur, we flew to the Grand Canyon National Park for one day and spent another at Hoover Dam. We did not swim in the pool, which seemed awfully crowded, as did all the pools we saw, especially the one at Mandalay Bay. We had a fantastic trip that our grandsons will never forget, and the Excalibur was part of the fun.	
