Aug 3 2009 	Nice pool area good staff but clearly a budget experience	We stayed had two adjoining tower II view rooms for three nights in July. We checked in at 3 pm and found the process to be much quicker and friendlier than at the MGM, Mandalay Bay or Monte Carlo. The rooms were decent size and the view of the NY NY and down the strip was ok. As other have mentioned they have a relatively large pool complex. More importantly, the pools weren't crowded and so you enough room to float around on rafts, play catch, etc. We rented a cabana for one of the days, which was nice albeit a bit expensive at $100. The only problems with the pool area were one of the slides being closed and because many guests leave their towels on the chairs when they leave, it can be hard to find a group of lounge chairs that you know for sure are unoccupied. Pool side drink service was also good. All that said, the place is a budget hotel. The furniture is worn, room service trays would stay in the halls for hours, and nothing in the place could be described as immaculate.On the upside, we never ran into the time share sales people that others have called ubiquitous. Nor did we have any problems with the room, which was quiet and cleaned promptly each day.One note of advice: You can't enter the self park from West bound Tropicana. If you are arriving via Las Vegas Blvd. turn in at any of the roads south of the hotel and work your way to the garage from the back of the hotel.	
Aug 3 2009 	Should Have Gotten Married There!	My husband and I took an early honeymoon.....long story. We got a great deal thru travelzoo for $31 USD/night at this hotel, June 3-10/09. We are getting married in September in costume. He will be a King and I'm going to be an Elizabethan Queen. This would have been a PERFECT place to get married, although it would have been just the two of us. In hindsight, it would have been ok. Instead we are doing the same thing here and we also have Medevil times here in Toronto. The hotel is beautiful, located near the end of the strip across from the MGM Grand and Tropicana and right smack beside New York New York. We rented a car for $155 for the whole week. Parking is free at all the hotels, which is unusual but awesome. That's what happens when a hotel actually wants your business! As far as the hotel itself goes, it's great for kids and adults. They have an arcade downstairs for kids. They have everything upstairs for adults. It's cool. We checked in with &quot;Jeff&quot;. He's awesome. We were friendly (at 1:30am their time) and he upgraded our room for free when I told him this was our official honeymoon before the wedding. Real sweetheart. We had a beautiful view of the 4 swimming pools and the beautiful Las Vegas mountain range every morning. I can see the Vegas strip any time. The beds were hard and we were unable to sleep the first night but we called housekeeping and had them put egg crate foam on our mattresses and then it was ok. They were awesome too. The rooms were nice, bathroom had a huge shower, no tub. Who needs a tub anyway. It was great for two to shower, which we did and enjoyed the big space to move around in. Water pressure was great, not like those dribbly showers in most hotels and we were on the 17th floor. We tipped the maid to NOT make our bed cause we don't like to pull the sheets out every night from the foot end. Nice. I'm told if you put clothes on the bed, the maid isn't allowed to make your bed. They can't touch your things. The only complaint I have about the hotel itself is that they seemed to be lacking in the ventilation department. Here in Ontario we aren't used to smoky casinos. It's a no no. They need to update their ventilation system because we found it the smokiest casino of all the hotels we went into. Other than that it was a fully self contained hotel. It even had a Starbucks, MacDonalds and plenty of other neat stores in it to shop around in. You didn't really have to leave the hotel for anything. They have the most AWESOME food deal on the strip. $25 all you can eat all day buffet. IT WAS WORTH EVERY DIME! The food was great. We never went hungry and because we had a car we could come and go as we pleased. I even bought a Lanyard and filled it with ice chips, ice cream and fruit juice. It made an awesome slushy. It was about 85-90 degrees of dry heat every day. If you tip the servers a couple of bucks they will get you extras you don't see on the buffet. My hubby loves lemon meringe pie. He mentioned it and they brought him a piece although we didn't see any out the whole week. We gave them extra tips for that.Most hotels, including this one, have escalators to take you everywhere and moving sidewalks. It's nice after walking for hours. Oh yeah, those creepy people at each entrance and all over the hotel who want to give you free stuff...... unless you have a day to waste, don't take their free stuff. They promise to only take 1-2 hours of your time &quot;depending on your level of interest&quot; and you also get a &quot;free lunch&quot;. You get your &quot;free stuff&quot; alright but friends of mine ended up going and the truth was they haul you off on a a buss to a resort far away so you are stranded and dependent on them. The 1-2 hours was more like 4-6 hours. The free lunch were stale sandwiches that they couldn't stomach and the time share...... oh did I forget to mention that? The timeshare was $40 000.00 plus $700 a month maintenance fee! Eeeeek! Of course the prices get cheaper when you argue but the bottom line was still expensive and the amount of time you get to spend every year goes down. Total rip off. Just smile and tell them you're not staying past today.The hotel spa and swimming poos was like none I've ever seen. They have a pool for kids, a pool for everyone, a pool for adults only and a pool for kids and the young at heart with a water fall and waterslide. It was nice. The lounge chairs are fairly new, comfortable and we NEVER had to fight over them because there were so many pools and so many lounges. Awesome! Nobody reserves them at 7 am and when you leave you take your towel and the next person gets the chair. Awesomely simple isn't it? Every night they clean the whole deck with a mini Zambone. The pools are not very deep but refreshing in the desert, just the right temperature. Only problem is the pool closes at 6. I like to go for a midnight dip or at least late night. During the day there are lifeguards everywhere. Oh yeah, please remember you're in the hot dry desert and dont' spend a 1/2 hour in the whirlpools..... duh! Some poor unfortunate soul ended up having a stroke in the hottub and they had to fish him out and take him to the hospital. Overall I would stay here again...... most definitely. We also say Hoover Dam and the Canyon, South Rim. Don't get ripped off at the West Rim , take the 5 1/2 hour drive to the South Rim. It's worth it. I know the new bridge is at the west rim but it'll cost ya an arm and a leg to get in and out and around. They don't allow you to take pictures off that glass bridge either. They'd rather sell you some. Take a bus tour, don't drive yourself either. It's a long and lonely ride through the desert.	
