May 16 2009 	Good value for money	I stayed at Excalibur from Sun 26 Apr to Wed 6 May and managed to get a good deal which worked out at around $50 per night for the 10 days I was there.Check in was on a Sun afternoon – I checked in 2 to 3 hours early which was no problem and the wait for check in was less than 10 mins.Tower 1 at Excalibur is still the older rooms and Tower 2 was recently remodelled to include widescreen televisions - I was put in Tower 1 but was on a fairly high floor (Floor 19) and have a good view of the MGM and Tropicana from my room.The room itself was fairly basic but had everything I needed.Room was a reasonable size (comparable to most Las Vegas strip rooms at the various casinos) and everything was cleanKing bed was comfortableHad a table with 2 chairs plus a separate lounge chair Plenty of drawers and wardrobe space for clothes etcBathroom was nothing spectacular but again was everything I needed.Housekeeping was efficient every day and had always been done by the time I returned to my room.If I had of taken my partner with me I am not sure she would have liked the room but for someone travelling on their room that just needed a reasonable place to sleep it was perfect.There are a few restaurants at the hotel and the food was ok without being anything special.They have a deal with the buffet where you pay $25 and that gives you an all day pass including breakfast/lunch/dinner – I heard from some other guests that it was one of the worst buffets in town so decided to give that a miss.They also have a food court up the escalators which includes McDonalds, Quiznos Subs, Pizza Hut, Krispy Kremes, and a few others.The casino is quite large – the sports book was one of the better ones on the strip which I found surprising – their poker room is a bit different because it uses the Poker Pro electronic tables – they have a few tournaments each day including a $20 buy in at 9am which generally gets at least 50 players.In terms of location the Excalibur is pretty decent.Just to the south you have Luxor and Mandalay Bay – either a short 5 to 10 min walk and they also have a free tram available between the 3 casinos – I found by the time you got the tram it was just as quick to walk anyway.Just to the north you have New York, MGM, Monte Carlo all within 10 mins walk.Planet Hollywood is about a 20 min walk and Bellagio is about a 25 min walk.The Deuce Bus service that runs up and down the strip was a good way to get further north to Mirage, Venetian, Wynn, Stratosphere etc – it actually goes all the way to Fremont Street - prices are only $3 for a single trip or $7 if you wanted an all day pass – if you are heading north then you need to go across the road and wait at the bus stop on Las Vegas Boulevard outside the Tropicana.	
